            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="chapter" data-narrate="true">
            <div class="chapter-title">üè° EPILOGUE: The New Beginning</div>

            <p>Brer Sheep went home to Briar County. Not to run a scam. Not to start a scheme. Just to... live.</p>

            <p>He got a job at Sister Ewe's brother's legitimate wool distribution company. He rented a small apartment. He attended weekly support group meetings. He paid his fines in installments.</p>

            <p>Was it glamorous? No. Was it exciting? Not particularly. Was it fulfilling? </p>

            <p>Surprisingly, yes.</p>

            <p>One year after graduation, Brer Sheep was having coffee with his old friends when Brer Bear brought up the past.</p>

            <div class="dialogue">
                <span class="character">Brer Bear</span>: "Remember when you ran that carnival with the rigged games?"<br><br>
                <span class="character">Brer Sheep</span>: "Yeah. I'm still sorry about that."<br><br>
                <span class="character">Brer Fox</span>: "And the bootleg movie theater?"<br><br>
                <span class="character">Brer Sheep</span>: "That too."<br><br>
                <span class="character">Brer Rabbit</span>: "Think you'll ever go back to it?"<br><br>
                <span class="character">Brer Sheep</span>: "Honestly? Every day I wake up and the thought crosses my mind. 'What if I just ran ONE small con?' But then I remember the rock pile. And Sister Ewe. And everyone at Woolly Meadows. And I remember I don't WANT to be that sheep anymore."<br><br>
                <span class="character">Brer Rabbit</span> (smiling): "Good answer."<br><br>
                <span class="character">Brer Sheep</span>: "Besides, my parole officer checks my bank account weekly. So there's that."
            </div>

            <p>They all laughed. Real laughs. Friend laughs. The kind of laughs you can only have when you've been through the fire and come out the other side.</p>

            <p>Brer Sheep wasn't perfect. He still had bad days. He still struggled with the urge to take shortcuts. But he had tools now. And support. And most importantly, he had a reason to stay straight.</p>

            <p>Because being ordinary wasn't a failure. It was freedom.</p>

